{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508644"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:08:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:08:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2818"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2818"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.04,0.34,0.49,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2807"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108933"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2807"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91302"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4228"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48451"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108933"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 88-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a mark on his face that has been present for many years. It has not bothered him in the past however recently it has become increasingly itchy and various family members have suggested that he should get it looked at. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, the lesion is clearly visible (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Imiquimod cream","Reassurance","Multiple punch biopsies","Complete excision with 2mm margin","Cryotherapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lesion on this man\u0027s face represents a symptomatic suspicious pigmented lesion and warrants biopsy. There are important concepts to understand around doing a biopsy of a pigmented lesion, and this case demonstrates a good example of when alternative methods may be required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor facial pigmented lesions suspicious of melanoma \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcisional biopsy with 2mm margins\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended where possible. This reduces sampling area associated with partial biopsies (e.g. punch or shave biopsies), which can result when biopsying lesions of heterogenous histological appearance, and result in missing cases of melanoma. This is important as 20-60% of melanomas can have associated components of melanocytic naevus. To put it in context, the false-negative diagnosis rates for punch, shave and excisional biopsies for pigmented lesions has been demonstrated to be 23.3%, 4.5% and\u00a01.7%, respectively. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever complete excision of facial lesions may not always be possible or practical due to large size, difficult location or being present in cosmetically sensitive areas, as is the case for this patient, as a complete excision would comprise of a very large surgical procedure and would lead to significant deformity of this patients face.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn these cases partial biopsy via shave or \u003Cstrong\u003Epunch biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E may be more appropriate, however it is important to ensure adequate samples have been taken to ensure diagnostic accuracy. Dermoscopy can be used to select the appropriate area for biopsy. In cases such as this it is often appropriate to do a few (two to three) mapping punch biopsies from different sites to ensure an accurate diagnosis is made and areas of invasive melanoma are not missed. For similar large lesions in different areas, it would also be appropriate to do multiple incisional biopsies to reduce the risk of missing the diagnosis. However, these types of biopsies must still be interpreted with great caution as the do not include the entire lesion. If in doubt considering referral to a dermatologist for biopsies and further management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as this is a pigmented lesion that is symptomatic and may represent a melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate because a formal diagnosis cannot be made and a potential melanoma missed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImiquimod cream\u003C/strong\u003E and radiation can be used for the management of less invasive forms of melanoma/pre-cancerous lesions such as lentigo maligna, but a formal pathology diagnosis must be made before these can be used.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pigmented lesions should be biopsied using a complete excision with margins depending on where they are located","Pigmented lesions require a pathology diagnosis before management can be instigated"],"references":["Oakley A. Lentigo maligna and lentigo maligna melanoma. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2011. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/lentigo-maligna-and-lentigo-maligna-melanoma/.","Beer T. Sampling suspicious pigmented lesions. Common Sense Pathology. In: Royal College of Pathologists Australiasia (RCPA) [online]. 2014. Available at: https://www.rcpa.edu.au/getattachment/95f458f9-3325-4501-848c-f01c0bc62506/Sampling-suspicious-pigmented-lesions.aspx.","Clarke P. Benign pigmented skin lesions. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2019;48:364-7. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/june/benign-pigmented-skin-lesions.","Ungureanu L, Vasilovici AF, Trufin II, et al. Lentigo Maligna Treatment\u2014An Update. J. Clin. Med. 2024, 13, 2527","Adybeik D, Ciranni D, Alaei L. Punch biopsy is best avoided for clinically suspicious pigmented lesions. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2019;48:354-6. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/june/punch-biopsy-is-best-avoided-for-clinically-suspic"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91302"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2818"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15280"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15280"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/08dd2d44-c998-4d95-a704-d5e09c045051.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/08dd2d44-c998-4d95-a704-d5e09c045051.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":500,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91302"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-15T08:29:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T07:07:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2807"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108933"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta